entry.title: Training AI to Become the Next Isaac Newton

media:group.media:title: Training AI to Become the Next Isaac Newton
media:group.media:description:
New Duke Engineering faculty member Boyuan Chen has taught AI to watch videos of physics phenomenon and successfully predict how many variables are at play in the equations defining their movement. That's the critical first step in deriving any fundamental understanding of a system's behavior.
Learn more about Chen at: https://pratt.duke.edu/about/news/boyuan-chen-making-general-purpose-robots-are-smarter-and-self-aware
Learn more about Chen's PhD work at Columbia University at: https://www.engineering.columbia.edu/news/lipson-chen-ai-alternative-physics

entry.title: DEID builds a suspended footbridge in Japo, Bolivia in 2022.

media:group.media:title: DEID builds a suspended footbridge in Japo, Bolivia in 2022.
media:group.media:description:
Student members of Duke Engineers for International Development traveled to Japo, Bolivia in the summer of 2022 to help construct a footbridge across a gorge that was impassible during seasonal rains. Watch the video to learn how the students built so much more!
Learn all about their experience at https://pratt.duke.edu/about/news/deid-returns-new-bridge-bolivia

media:group.media:title: POV: You're a drone.
media:group.media:description: Duke University sent a team of students and mentors to Costa Rica's La Selva Research Station to learn how to pilot drones and collect information about rainforest biodiversity. The team has now advanced to the semifinals of the $10 million XPRIZE Rainforest competition.

media:group.media:title: Metamorphic Materials
media:group.media:description:
Watch this thin, flexible material teach itself to mimic ocean waves and flexing palms in real-time. Relying on electromagnetic actuation, mechanical modeling and machine learning to form new configurations, the surface can even learn to adapt to hindrances such as broken elements, unexpected constraints or changing environments.
Learn more about the research at: https://pratt.duke.edu/about/news/metamorphic-materials Learn more about Dr. Xiaoyue Ni's lab here: http://ni.pratt.duke.edu/

entry.title: PreMiEr ERC - Precision Microbiome Engineering Research Center

media:group.media:title: PreMiEr ERC - Precision Microbiome Engineering Research Center
media:group.media:description:
The Engineering Research Center for Precision Microbiome Engineering, or PreMiEr, aims to develop diagnostic tools and engineering approaches that promote building designs for preventing the colonization of harmful bacteria, fungi or viruses while encouraging beneficial microorganisms. PreMiEr is funded by a five-year, $26 million grant from the National Science Foundation (NSF), renewable for a second five-year, $26 million term. Joining Duke in the effort are researchers from North Carolina Agricultural and Technical State University, the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill, the University of North Carolina at Charlotte, and North Carolina State University. Learn more at https://pratt.duke.edu/about/news/premier-nsf-erc
More stories from Duke Engineering Now: https://pratt.duke.edu/about/news/duke-engineering-now

entry.title: Growing Neurons to Heal Brain Damage

media:group.media:title: Growing Neurons to Heal Brain Damage
media:group.media:description: Watch as primordial neural cells dance across, grow into, and even move 3D scaffolds engineered to heal brain injury from stroke and other trauma. Decorating the scaffold with various nutrients and biochemical signals allow researchers to control what types of brain tissues they become. Learn more at https://pratt.duke.edu/about/news/npc-growth-scaffold
